	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10236827148991><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>RE: O</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73658><span id=Sage>DavivMcD</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>300 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Jun 10th 12:26 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.21]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I likewise have always appreciated your insightful and rogue pride-inspiring posts. And I usually agree with your posts. But this time I think you are exaggerating the effect of strength. So I hope you don't take any personal offense at my arguments.<br><br>You may have misunderstood my original post. I said that thesafehouse.org's equation didn't include damage bonuses. But I did. I didn't exactly explain it, but I first calculated the damage bonus you get by looking at the difference between the equation's estimate and what your actual max is. Then I reapplied that bonus, numerically and percentage-wise, to the estimate with 120 strength. I admit I hadn't thought that strength might affect the damage bonus. I had always assumed that damage bonus was just a small multiplier that was based only on your level and the weapon you're using.<br><br>What I do know is that I have tested out that equation, and I swear by it. Up until level 30, it has stayed accurate within 1%. And even with a rogue 17 levels past level 30, it was off by a factor of only 12%. Why do you say I'm off by 50%? Now, assuming that the extra damage bonus is dependant directly on strength (which is not likely but possible), the ratio of the damage bonus w/ 120 strength to one w/ 197 strength is 120/197, or about 61%. The extimate for this is a backstab of 313. Would you really put aside DEX and AGI and boost your already good strength up 77 very expensive points, just to get 19 extra damage on your best backstab? I'm just saying to look at your situation. Verant's not stupid. They wouldn't make any single stat so vital to rogues that they could simply become uber by maxing out that stat and forgetting the rest. Instead of boosting your strength as high as possible, you should look at your other melee stats and try to get them all as high as possible while keeping them closer to each other. At least get your STA above 100 to get that mysterious stat bonus. <br><br>Now, I may be entirely wrong here. And if I am I heartily apologize. But every fact I have seen so far has just led me to believe I am right. Like you said, no one knows what Verant's exact equations are. So don't just argue back at me by saying I'm wrong. Put some facts down. You said there's a huge difference with different strengths. How can you tell? When was the last time you actually had only 120 strength? And even if you took off equipment until you had 120 strength, you have to experiment for a long time to make sure you're not getting near your max. I mean you can't just get one bad backstab and say &quot;See! I got a crappy backstab because I have crappy strength!&quot; I don't mean that as an insult, but as a challenge. Experiment with less strength, and make sure you test lots of backstabs. To be statistically accurate, you should get at least 100 backstabs with each different strength you try before making any concrete assumptions. And take the average of all your backstabs, as well as your max hits. I'm challenging you to do this instead of doing it myself basically because I'm only 30 and I don't get any sizeable damage bonuses yet. Which reminds me, my max backstab (166) is exactly half yours! It was with a 12-dmg weapon at level 28. Hope to hear your reply soon!<br>&nbsp;<br>Daviv McD (Un-retired!)<br>36th Dwarf Rogue<br>Fury Fighters<br>Xegony<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233</a></td></tr>
